594 2.69769C11.8194 2.45769 11.7044 2.17769 11.7144 1.85769C11.7244 1.53769 11.8394 1.25769 12.0594 1.01769C12.2994 0.777688 12.5844 0.652688 12.9144 0.642688C13.2444 0.632688 13.5294 0.747688 13.7694 0.987688L19.2594 6.47769C19.3794 6.59769 19.4644 6.72769 19.5144 6.86769C19.5644 7.00769 19.5894 7.15769 19.5894 7.31769C19.5894 7.47769 19.5644 7.62769 19.5144 7.76769C19.4644 7.90769 19.3794 8.03769 19.2594 8.15769L13.7694 13.6477C13.5294 13.8877 13.2444 14.0027 12.9144 13.9927C12.5844 13.9827 12.2994 13.8577 12.0594 13.6177C11.8394 13.3777 11.7244 13.0977 11.7144 12.7777C11.7044 12.4577 11.8194 12.1777 12.0594 11.9377L15.4794 8.51769Z"></path></svg></button></div></div><div class="relative z-[2] grid grid-cols-1 gap-x-6 gap-y-12 rounded-2xl bg-sand p-10 sm:grid-cols-2"><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="true"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Apo Island</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">A 30-minute boat ride from the resort, Apo Island is a protected marine sanctuary renowned for its vibrant coral reefs and diverse marine life. Apo is also ideal for snorkeling and diving, with sightings of turtles and colorful tropical fish. Most notably, the reef exhibit at the Shedd Aquarium in Chicago is patterned after Apo Island.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="true"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Sumilon</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Sumilon Island is the first marine sanctuary established in 1973. Sumilon offers stunning wall dives and a variety of marine ecosystems, from coral gardens to sandy bottoms. Divers can explore rich biodiversity, including large schools of fish and the occasional reef shark.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="true"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Oslob Whale Shark</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Dive with gentle giants at Oslob, where you can encounter whale sharks up close. This unique experience allows divers to observe these magnificent creatures in their natural habitat.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="true"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Masaplod Norte</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Masaplod Norte features an artificial reef created from old tires, attracting a plethora of macro life. Divers can discover schools of Yellow Snappers, Bluefin Trevally, and even Green Turtles, alongside fascinating macro critters.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Masaplod Sur</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">At Masaplod Sur, divers can explore two reef patches separated by sandy gullies. The site is home to diverse macro subjects, including robust Ghost Pipefish and elusive Frogfish, making it an excellent location for macro enthusiasts.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>San Miguel Point</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">San Miguel Point is famous for its sandy bottom and rich macro life, including the stunning stiliger and ship Nudibranchs. Divers may also encounter cuttlefish and flamboyant cuttlefish, making it a must-visit for macro photography.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Talisay Point</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Just a three-minute boat ride from the resort, Talisay Point features a sandy slope adorned with corals. Here, divers can spot Harlequin Shrimp, Nudibranchs, and Frogfish in a vibrant underwater environment.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Pyramid</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Pyramid is an artificial reef known for its macro diving opportunities. Discover Thorny Seahorses, Sawblade Shrimp hiding in black corals, and a variety of Nudibranchs, making it a captivating site for underwater exploration.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Dauin Sur</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Dauin South boasts thriving coral reefs teeming with marine life. Divers can encounter Garden Eels, turtles, giant clams, and blue ribbon eels, all thriving in this diverse underwater ecosystem.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Ginama-an</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Meaning “man-made” in the local language, Ginama-an features an artificial reef made from old tires. This site attracts a variety of reef fish and crustaceans, with vibrant sponges and corals creating a colorful underwater habitat.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Dauin Norte</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Dauin Norte is the most popular dive site for good reason. With a sandy slope leading to a healthy reef, divers can see Ghost Pipefish, Frogfish, and a multitude of reef fish, including regular sightings of Green and Hawksbill Turtles.</div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-6 data-[visible=false]:hidden" data-visible="false"><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-3"><svg width="16" height="30" viewBox="0 0 16 30" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g opacity="0.9"><circle cx="7.68293" cy="7.68293" r="7.68293"></circle><rect x="7" y="11.7075" width="2" height="18.2927"></rect></g></svg><h3>Punta</h3></div><hr class="border-t-2 opacity-30"/><div class="">Punta, meaning “Corner,” is located at the southern end of the beach and features a sandy slope home to unique species like Pink-Eared Mantis Shrimp and various octopuses. Divers appreciate the potential for current and the opportunity to photograph rare cephalopods.</div></div></div></div><img src="<?php echo THEME_URI ?>/media/topographic-3.svg" class="pointer-events-none absolute left-0 top-0 z-[1] size-full object-cover object-center opacity-10"/></section><section class="relative bg-[#99C2D3] py-25"><img src="<?php echo THEME_URI ?>/media/topographic-3.svg" class="pointer-events-none absolute left-0 top-0 h-full w-full object-cover object-center opacity-10"/><div class="flex min-w-0 flex-row justify-center overflow-clip"><div class="marquee-left flex shrink-0 flex-row gap-4 px-2 sm:gap-6 sm:px-3"><img src="<?php echo THEME_URI ?>/media/dive/fish-1.jpg" alt="" class="h-[175px] w-[225px] rounded-[3rem] bg-black object-cover object-center sm:h-[250px] sm:w-[300px] sm:rounded-[5rem]"/><img src="<?php echo THEME_URI ?>/media/dive/fish-2.jpg" alt="" class="h-[175px] w-[225px] rounded-[3rem] bg-black object-cover object-center sm:h-[250px] sm:w-